## Issue Schema

Each issue carries:

|Field      |Type       |Values                                          |
|-----------|-----------|------------------------------------------------|
|Title      |Native     |Descriptive, agent-readable                     |
|Description|Native body|Full context, markdown                          |
|Status     |Native     |Backlog / Ready / In Progress / In Review / Done|
|Issue Type |Native     |Feature / Story / Bug                           |
|Milestone  |Native     |Named phase e.g. v2.4                           |
|Priority   |Custom     |High / Medium / Low                             |
|Reported By|Custom     |Any agent or Jeremy                             |
|Owner      |Custom     |Any agent or Jeremy                             |

Labels: reserved, not in use yet.
Assignees: Jeremy only (GitHub accounts required — agents use Owner field instead).

-----

## How Issues Get Created — Current Protocol

**Bond generates a CSV** formatted as:

```
title,body,milestone
"Issue title","Full description. Reported by [Agent]. Owner: [Agent].",v2.4
```

**Jeremy runs one command** from the Meta1 local folder:

```
githubCsvTools issues-YYYYMMDD.csv
```

Issues appear in the repo. Jeremy then sets Issue Type, Priority, Owner, and Reported By fields in the GitHub Projects UI.

**Limitation:** The CSV tool sets title, body, and milestone only. Custom fields are a manual UI step for now. This is accepted as temporary scaffolding.

-----

## How Issues Get Updated — Current Protocol

Manual. Jeremy updates status, priority, and field values in the GitHub Projects UI as work progresses. Bond monitors and reports in sessions.

